Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

by Progress Akpelu¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

# Covert LoanStatus and EmploymentStatus into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dic = {'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed', 'Full-time', 'Self-employed', 'Not available', 'Other',
                                  'Part-time', 'Not employed', 'Retired'],
                  'LoanStatus': ['Current', 'Completed', 'Chargedoff', 'Defaulted', 'Past Due (1-15 days)', 
                                 'Past Due (31-60 days)', 'Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (91-120 days)',
                                 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 'FinalPaymentInProgress',
                                 'Past Due (>120 days)', 'Cancelled'],
                  'IncomeRange': ['$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$100,000+', '$75,000-99,999',
                                  'Not displayed', '$1-24,999', 'Not employed', '$0']}

for var in ordinal_var_dic:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dic[var])
    loan_set[var] = loan_set[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • What factors affect a loan’s outcome status?
  • What affects the borrower’s APR or interest rate?
  • Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • IncomeRange - The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  • DebToIncomeRatio - The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  • ProsperScore - A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • ProsperRating - The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

EmploymentStatus: This showed that most of the borrowers who recieved the loan are employed.

LoanStatus: This showed that the the current borrowers above 50,000 are yet to pay their loans.

IncomeRange: This showed that people who earned 25k to 75k were given more of the loan. Showing that the higher the income the more the chance of being given a loan.

MonthlyLoanPayment: This showed that most of the borrowers paid little of the monthly repayment plan.

Bivariate Exploration¶

To start with, i will look at the pairwise correlation of the data to see if there are correlations between the variables

In [27]:
numeric_vars = ['BorrowerRate', 'BorrowerAPR', 'MonthlyLoanPayment', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 'LoanOriginalAmount',
                'ProsperScore', 'StatedMonthlyIncome']
In [28]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])

sb.heatmap(loan_set[numeric_vars].corr(), annot=True, fmt='.3f', cmap='vlag_r', center=0)
plt.title('Heatmap showing correlation between the variables')
plt.show();

The heatmap shows there is a strong correlation between BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR. That's they are both directly proportional. There is a negative correlation between the ProsperScore and BorrowerRate. Meaning the higher the Score, the lower the interest rate. It shows there is a strong positive correlation between the original loan amount and the monthly loan payment.

Conclusions¶

From the analysis, the Prosper Loan Service gives loans to indviduals. To be able to access the loan, there are criterials the company uses in other to assess the indiduals' payback ability. This is to ensure the borrowers pay back within the minimum time possible. Such ciriterials include and not limited to Employment status, individuals monthly income and if the individuals have any collateral which in this case is house. These factors are then considered to be rate and score the individual, Prosper rating and Prosper score respectively. As such, the interest rate and annual interest rate are inversely proportional to these factors.

Our findings showed that the those are employed and own a home were mostly considered for the loan. Those that are employed, own a home and earn more are got higher prosper score and rating and as such high interest rate and lower annual interest rate. While those who are employed, earned average salaries and without a home were rated and score lower which resulted to higher interest rate and annual interest rate as well.

Futhermore, we saw that there was a correlation between the loan original amount and the monthly loan payment. That's, those who collected higher amount paid more monthly.
